---

# 2. cmd/

Contains executable applications.

Every executable has exactly one entry point.

Examples:

* Hypervisor
* Registry
* Wallet daemon
* Validator daemon
* CLI

---

# 3. internal/

Contains implementation.

Packages inside internal SHALL NOT be imported by external applications.

---

# 4. providers/

Contains Provider implementations.

Every Provider implements RFC-0022.

Provider packages SHALL NOT communicate directly with each other.

---

# 5. sdk/

Public Go SDK.

Third-party developers implement custom Providers using this SDK.

---

# 6. proto/

Protocol definitions.

Contains:

* gRPC
* protobuf
* OpenAPI

---

# 7. docs/

Contains:

* RFC documents
* IMP documents
* ADR documents
* Developer Guides
* Architecture documentation

---

# 8. configs/

Contains example configuration files.

Production secrets SHALL NOT be committed.

---

# 9. migrations/

Contains database schema migrations.

All schema evolution SHALL be version controlled.

---

# 10. scripts/

Contains:

* build scripts;
* packaging scripts;
* development helpers;
* testing utilities;
* release automation.

---

# 11. testdata/

Contains:

* reference Bundles;
* sample Endpoint Manifests;
* validation fixtures;
* synthetic workloads.

---

# 12. web/

Contains the Operator Dashboard.

The dashboard SHALL remain a client of the public Hypervisor API.

Business logic SHALL NOT exist in the frontend.

---

# 13. Design Rules

Every package SHALL have one clearly defined responsibility.

Cross-package communication SHALL occur only through interfaces.

No package SHALL import another package solely for convenience.

Circular dependencies are prohibited.

The repository SHALL remain navigable without project-specific knowledge.
